title: Establishment of Working Group on Oral Health and Dental Care
content_text: The Chief Executive announced in his 2022 Policy Address that a comprehensive review of the dental care services provided or subsidised by the Government will be conducted, covering the relevant policy objectives, service scope and service delivery model. The new Working Group will review the existing dental care services and advise the Government on the long-term strategy for oral health and dental care, as well as matters including enhancement of the scope and mode of the services.  Chaired by the Permanent Secretary for Health, the Working Group comprises non-official members and five ex-officio members for a two-year tenure lasting from December 31, 2022, to December

members for a two-year tenure lasting from December 31, 2022, to December 31, 2024. The Working Group will hold its first meeting in the first quarter of 2023. Non-official members comprise representatives from the dental profession, healthcare sector, collaborating non-governmental organisations of government-subsidised dental care programmes, as well as well-regarded and relevant community personalities. They have rich experience and extensive knowledge in relevant areas and will provide invaluable insights and advice to the Government on the future development of dental care services in Hong Kong.  Specifically, the Working Group will advise the Government on the following

dental care services in Hong Kong.  Specifically, the Working Group will advise the Government on the following aspects: (1) the scope, efficacy and cost-effectiveness of the existing oral health measures and dental care services undertaken by the Government, having regard to local circumstances and experience as well as overseas practices and evidence; (2) the long-term strategy for oral health and dental care in Hong Kong, in particular as part of primary healthcare, including co-ordination of service programmes and manpower provision with a view to enhancing the oral health of the community; and (3) priority areas for enhancements to oral health measures and dental care services, including

community; and (3) priority areas for enhancements to oral health measures and dental care services, including the level of essential primary dental care services required by the citizens at different life stages, the scope of publicly provided or funded dental care services, and the mode(s) of delivery and financing.
